Monte Carlo simulations in statistics are computer experiments involving random sampling from probablility distributions to study properties of statistical methods.

We use Monte Carlo (MC) simulation for the following purposes:

  • Inference when the distribution of the test statistic is not known analytically.

  • Comparing or assessing performances of inferential methods when parametric assumptions are violated.

  • Testing the null and alternative hypotheses under various conditions.

  • Evaluating the performance of inferential methods (e.g. power calculations).

  • Comparing the quality of estimators.

Basic Monte Carlo:¶

  • We estimate the distribution of the statistic by randomly sampling from the same population of interest and recording the value of statistic for each sample.
  • The observed values of the statistic for these samples are used to estimate the distribution of statistic.
  • By this way, we do not need to use some assumptions to make an inference about the statistic. (eg. In hypothesis testing for mean, we do not need to make an assumption that sample mean is approximately distributed normal. Since, in Monte Carlo method, we use emprical distribution of statistic, which is coming from random samples.)

Q1)¶

Use Monte Carlo integration with control variates to estimate

$$ I = \int_0^3 \frac{e^{-2x}}{1+x^2} + (4x+2)^2 dx $$

That means that our g(X) function is $ \frac{e^{-2x}}{1+x^2} + (4x+2)^2 $. Then, we should find another function f(X), that should be correlated (similar to) g(X) function. $f(X) = \frac{1}{1+x^2}$ may be correlated with g(X), because it is similar with g(X). Thus, we choose f(X) as $\frac{1}{1+x^2}$.¶

Let first find normal estimate of the integral using simple monte carlo integration.¶

In [ ]:
#define parameters
n <- 10^5
a <- 0; b <- 3
x <- runif(n,a,b)

#define f(X)

g <- function(x) exp(-2*x) / (1+x^2) + (4*x + 2)^2

# estimate g(X.bar)*(b-a)

estimate <- mean(sapply(x,g)) * (b-a)
estimate
In [ ]:
real_integral <- integrate(g, a, b)
real_integral
In [ ]:
var.estimate <- var(sapply(x,g))
var.estimate <- mean(sapply(x,g)^2) - (mean(sapply(x, g)))^2
var.estimate

Then, use control variates¶

$$ 1)\ c^* = \frac{((),())}{(())} $$$$ 2)\ \hat \theta_c = g(X) + c^*(f(Y) - \theta) $$

where $\theta$ is the real value of the integral and we can find it using integrate function in R.

$$ 3)\ (_{c^*}) = Var(g(X)) - \frac{[((),())]^2}{(())} $$
In [ ]:
#define parameters
n <- 10^4
a <- 0; b <- 3
x <- runif(n,a,b)

#define f(X) and g(X)

g.cont <- function(x) exp(-2*x) / (1+x^2) + (4*x+2)^2
f.cont <- function(x) 1/(1+x^2)


# est of c*

cor(g.cont(x),f.cont(x)) # correlation is high, we satisfy the correlation between f and g.

c_star <- -cov(g.cont(x),f.cont(x)) / var(f.cont(x))
c_star


estimate_cont = mean(g.cont(x) + c_star * (f.cont(x) - (1/(b-a)) * integrate(f.cont,a,b)$value))*(b-a)

cat("Estimate using control variates is", estimate_cont)
In [ ]:
var.cont.estimate <- var(g.cont(x) + c_star * (f.cont(x) - (1/(b-a)) *integrate(f.cont, a, b)$value))
var.cont.estimate

Q2)¶

Let X ~ Beta(2,3). The Beta density is;

$$ f(x; \alpha, \beta)=\frac{\Gamma(\alpha +\beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha)+\Gamma(\beta)}x^{\alpha-1}(1-x)^{\beta-1}, 0 \leq x \leq 1 $$

CDF of Beta distribution;

$$ F(X) = P(X \leq x) = \int_0^x \frac{\Gamma(\alpha +\beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha)+\Gamma(\beta)}x^{\alpha-1}(1-x)^{\beta-1}, 0 \leq x \leq 1 $$

(Note that $\Gamma(t)= (t-1)!$)

Estimate P(X < 0.3) using Monte Carlo Integration with bothcontrol variates and then calculate the percent variance reduction. Plot that probability.

$$ P(X < 0.3) = \int_0^{0.3} \frac{\Gamma(\alpha +\beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha)+\Gamma(\beta)}x^{\alpha-1}(1-x)^{\beta-1} $$
In [ ]:
#define parameters
n <- 10^4
a <- 0; b <- 0.3
x <- runif(n,a,b)

alpha <- 2
beta <- 3



#define f(X) and g(X)

g.cont <- function(x) factorial(alpha+beta-1)/(factorial(alpha-1)*factorial(beta-1))*x^(alpha-1)*(1-x)^(beta-1)
f.cont <- function(x) x*(1-x)


# est of c*

cor(g.cont(x),f.cont(x)) # correlation is high, we satisfy the correlation between f and g.

c_star_beta <- -cov(g.cont(x),f.cont(x)) / var(f.cont(x))
c_star_beta


estimate_cont_beta = mean(g.cont(x) + c_star_beta * (f.cont(x) - (1/(b-a))*integrate(f.cont, a, b)$value))*(b-a)

cat("Estimate using control variates is", estimate_cont_beta)

Q3)¶

Suppose that $_1, _2, _3, _4$ are i.i.d. from a standard normal distribution. Estimate the sum of their squares $ = ^2_1 + ^2_2 + ^2_3 + ^2_4$ , E(Y).

We know that if $X \sim N(0,1)$, and $X^2 \sim \chi^2_1$,

Then; $\sum_{i=0}^n X_i^2 \sim \chi^2_n$

In [1]:
M <- 1000
y <- numeric(M)
for(i in 1:M){
x <- rnorm(4,0,1)
y[i] <- sum(x^2)
}
estimate <- mean(y)
estimate
4.00574721114075

Also we know that

$ \sim \chi^2_4\ ( ) = 4$

Q4)¶

Suppose that you are tossing a biased coin $(_ = 0.6)$ 15 times. What is the probability to obtain more than 10 Heads? Repeat this experiment by taking sample size n=10, n=100, n=1000, n=10000, and n=100000.

Binomial Probability:¶

Let random variable X is the number of Heads obtained and $ \sim Binomial(, )$

$$ ( > 10) = ( = 11) + ... + ( = 15) $$

Monte Carlo Simulation:¶

  1. Draw 15 random variables $x_i$ from Uniform(0,1), i = 1,,15

  2. Define Head if $x_i \leq 0.6$,Tail otherwise

  1. Count the number of Heads, if the number of Heads are more than 10, increse the count k.

  2. Repeat step 2 and 3 N times

  3. The desired probability is approximately k/N

Monte Carlo Probability¶

In [2]:
N <- 10^seq(1,5)
for(j in 1:length(N)){
k <- 0 # counter for heads
for(i in 1:N[j]){
x <- runif(15)
num_heads <- sum(x<=0.6)

    
# Alternatively
# x <- sample(c("H","T"), size = 15, replace = T)
# num_heads <- sum(x == "H")
if(num_heads > 10){
k <- k + 1
}
}
est_prob <- k/N[j]
cat("When N is",N[j],"estimated probability is",est_prob,"\n")
}

When N is 10 estimated probability is 0.2 
When N is 100 estimated probability is 0.29 
When N is 1000 estimated probability is 0.223 
When N is 10000 estimated probability is 0.2131 
When N is 1e+05 estimated probability is 0.21632

True Probability Value¶

In [3]:
exact_prob <- 0
for(j in 11:15){
exact_prob <- exact_prob + dbinom(j,15,0.6)
}
cat("Exact probability is",round(exact_prob,5),"\n","\n")

Exact probability is 0.21728

Q6)¶

Consider, we want to calculate the bias of the estimators of location and scale parameters of normal distribution $(\mu = 3, \sigma^2 = 5)$ when we have sample with sizes 5, 30 and 100.

$$ f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt {2 \pi \sigma^2}}e^{\frac{(x- \mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}},\ -\infty<x<\infty $$

We know that bias of estimator T is given by

$$ Bias(\hat T) = (\hat T) $$

Empirically, we can find the estimated bias by using

$$ \hat {Bias(\hat T)} = \frac{\sum_{i=0}^M \hat T_i}{M} - T $$

Where $\hat T_i$ is the $i^{th}$ estimator coming from $i^{th}$ sample (we have M different sample mean to calculate the empirical distribution of the $\hat T$)

We can obtain the M different samples by using the true distribution of the $(_1, _2, ..., _n)$ which is the normal distribution with mean $\mu$ and variance $\sigma^2$.

Let;

$$ _1 = \mu \hat T_1 = \bar X\ \text{for location parameter}\\ _2 = \sigma^2 \hat T_2 = ^2\ \text{for scale parameter} $$
In [5]:
T1 <- 3; T2 <- 5 # set parameters
n <- c(5,30,100) # sample sizes
M <- 10^5 #simulation



# creating an empty matrix to store bias values for both t1&t2
bias <- matrix(0,ncol = length(n), nrow = 2,
dimnames = list(c("T1 bias","T2 bias"),
c(paste(rep("n",length(n)),n,sep=""))))



m <- numeric(M)
v <- numeric(M)


for(j in 1:length(n)){
    for(i in 1:M){
        x <- rnorm(n[j],mean = T1,sd = sqrt(T2))
        
        m[i] <- mean(x)
        v[i] <- var(x)
}

    bias[1,j] <- mean(m) - T1
    bias[2,j] <- mean(v) - T2
}
round(bias,4)
n5n30n100
T1 bias0.0023 0.0018 -0.0004
T2 bias0.0047 0.0063 -0.0036
